---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Chris Walker — Walker Design Studio | Heat & Glo Architects" description="Chris Walker of Walker Design Studio specifies Heat & Glo Mezzo for contemporary residential projects where the linear fireplace functions as structural composition, not decoration." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="position:relative; min-height:520px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; overflow:hidden;">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/37b85921-3a11-497e-8bfb-05d7710ce531/HNG-Cosmo-32-Open-Floor-Plan-tif"
      alt="Heat & Glo Cosmo 32 gas fireplace in an open-floor-plan contemporary residential living room with clean linear geometry"
      style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center;"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div style="position:absolute; inset:0; background:linear-gradient(to top, rgba(10,10,12,0.85) 0%, rgba(10,10,12,0.42) 55%, rgba(10,10,12,0.1) 100%);"></div>
    <div style="position:relative; max-width:820px; padding:3rem 2rem; color:#fff;">
      <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b8d0e8; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Designer Feature</p>
      <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem); font-weight:800; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Chris Walker</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:400; opacity:0.9; margin:0;">Walker Design Studio &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Contemporary Residential</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main style="max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 1.5rem;">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">The Fireplace as Structural Composition</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Contemporary residential design has a problem with fire. The aesthetic vocabulary it reaches for, flat planes, restrained material palettes, the absence of applied ornament, has an instinct to eliminate anything that reads as decorative. The fireplace, with its surround, its mantel, its visual mass, looks like a candidate for elimination. Walker Design Studio's work is built on the argument that this is exactly wrong.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Chris Walker's position is that the fireplace in a contemporary home should be more present, not less, because the rest of the interior is working with restraint. Strip the room of pattern and applied detail and what remains is form, material, and light. Fire is all three simultaneously. A well-specified linear fireplace in a white plaster or board-formed concrete surround is not decoration, it is the room's primary event. Everything else takes its orientation from it.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Walker Design Studio's project vocabulary is consistent: open plans, material precision, clean edges, and a disciplined restraint that makes the fireplace the room's most consequential decision. Chris approaches the hearth specification as he approaches structure. It is not finish work. It is the first line of the composition.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
    <section style="border-left:4px solid #2a4a72; padding:1.25rem 1.75rem; background:#f2f5f9; margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; line-height:1.7; color:#2a2a2a; font-style:italic; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
        "In a contemporary interior, you have fewer elements doing the work. That means every element carries more weight. The Mezzo is the right tool because it reads as architecture, not as furniture. It doesn't need a mantel to justify itself. It just needs a clear wall and enough room to breathe."
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.8125rem; color:#6b6b6b; margin:0; font-style:normal; letter-spacing:0.04em; text-transform:uppercase;">Paraphrased from Chris Walker's ProAdvantage program onboarding &mdash; illustrative, not a verified direct quotation</p>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY HEAT & GLO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Why Walker Design Studio Specifies Heat &amp; Glo</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The Mezzo Series appears consistently in Walker Design Studio's project portfolio for a set of reasons that are architectural before they are aesthetic. The linear format of the Mezzo works within the horizontal emphasis of contemporary residential architecture. Wide, low proportions, extended glazing lines, and open-plan living volumes all have a horizontal grammar. A traditional firebox interrupts that grammar. A linear unit reinforces it.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The Mezzo's ribbon flame profile is the other critical factor. In an open-plan room where the fireplace is visible from the kitchen, the dining area, and the main seating zone simultaneously, the flame has to read correctly from multiple vantage points and at varying distances. The Mezzo's flame has the visual depth to reward close viewing without becoming theatrical from across the room. Crystal glass media and a black interior surround keep the unit self-contained, which lets the surrounding material, whether that is a poured concrete panel, a large-format tile, or a flush plaster chase, carry the compositional statement.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Chris also draws on the Primo II in projects where the fireplace separates two distinct living zones without a full wall closure. The see-through capability of the Primo II gives Walker Design Studio the ability to create spatial definition in an open plan without surrendering light or visual connection. It is a partition that is also an amenity, which is exactly the kind of dual-use thinking that contemporary residential clients expect from their design team.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- TYPICAL PROJECT SHAPE -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">The Shape of a Walker Design Studio Project</h2>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:600; color:#2a4a72; margin:0 0 1rem;">Restraint as Practice, Not Trend</h3>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        A Walker Design Studio residential engagement typically involves a client who has moved through a sequence of interior design relationships and arrived at a specific conclusion: they want less. Not fewer things in a poverty sense, but a more disciplined editorial practice where every element in the room is there because it has earned its place. Chris works with that client well because the Walker Design Studio method begins with subtraction.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Hearth decisions in a Walker project are made early and held firm. The fireplace unit, its surround material, and its relationship to the floor plane and ceiling height are established in schematic design and rarely revisited. This early lock-in benefits the contractor coordination process, and it is one reason Chris has developed a consistent working relationship with the Heat and Glo ProAdvantage program, which provides the technical documentation and dealer access that support early-stage specification without requiring repeated follow-up.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        The typical Walker client occupies the home as a primary residence and uses it throughout the year. The fireplace is a daily feature in cooler months, not a seasonal statement piece. IntelliFire's remote operation and scheduling capabilities support that pattern of use, removing friction from a feature that, in a well-designed Walker interior, should be as easy to use as a light switch.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 1 -->
    <section style="background:#1a1a1a; color:#fff; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b8d0e8; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Trade Program</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Join ProAdvantage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; opacity:0.8; margin:0;">Dedicated trade support, priority access, and project resources for design professionals.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/pro/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Explore ProAdvantage</a>
    </section>

    <!-- INSTALLATION CARDS -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1.5rem;">Sample Installations in the Walker Register</h2>
      <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr)); gap:1.5rem;">

        <!-- Card 1 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/c0885ec5-e68c-48f7-9a85-f66e09730cd3/img-pdp-cosmo-room-shot-01-jpg"
              alt="Heat & Glo Cosmo gas fireplace installed in a contemporary living room with high ceilings and ribbon flame"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Mezzo Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Contemporary Living Room Feature</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Linear format, ribbon flame, crystal glass media. Architecture, not furniture. The Mezzo does not need a mantel to justify itself.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 2 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/b6184228-9ae0-4732-a39e-cb404169cd75/Primo-II-Driftwood_Logs"
              alt="Heat & Glo Primo II with driftwood log set and amber flame in a contemporary residential installation"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Primo II Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Open-Plan Zone Divider</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Linear fireplace wall anchors an open contemporary plan. Low-profile seating oriented toward the flame. TV overhead, stair volume beyond.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 3 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/0f96fb5a-749f-465f-936d-046b6e0496ed/HNG_Slimline_Fusion_RefBlkGlass_OakLogs_GunMetalCleanFace_pdp"
              alt="Heat & Glo Slimline Fusion with reflective black glass, oak logs, and gunmetal clean face — the full contemporary product range"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Full Lineup</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Inspiration Gallery</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">The breadth of the Heat and Glo lineup across installation types. Walker Design Studio draws on this range across a varied project portfolio.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 2 -->
    <section style="background:#f2f5f9; border:1px solid #c0ccdb; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#2a4a72; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Dealer Network</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Find a Local Dealer</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Connect with a Heat and Glo dealer for contemporary fireplace spec sheets, clearance documentation, and showroom access near your project.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Dealer Locator</a>
    </section>

    <p style="color:#888; font-size:0.875rem; border-top:1px solid #e5e0db; padding-top:1.5rem;"><a href="/architect/" style="color:#c44a08; text-decoration:none;">Back to all architects</a></p>
  </main>

</BaseLayout>
